"Zaehle S., Sitch S., Smith B., Hatterman F.","Effects of parameter uncertainties on the modeling of terrestrial biosphere dynamics",2005,"Global Biogeochemical Cycles","19","3", GB3020,"1","16",,,10.1029/2004GB002395,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-27744432540&partnerID=40&md5=45244220d77c17cf5cf1dc7c641264df","Department of Global Change and Natural Systems, Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research (PIK), P.O. Box 60 12 0, D-14412 Potsdam, Germany; Joint Centre for Hydro-Meteorological Research (JCHMR), Met Office, Wallingford OX10 8BB, United Kingdom; Physical Geography and Ecosystems Analysis, Geobiosphere Science Centre, Lund University, Sölvegatan 12, S-22362 Lund, Sweden","Zaehle, S., Department of Global Change and Natural Systems, Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research (PIK), P.O. Box 60 12 0, D-14412 Potsdam, Germany; Sitch, S., Department of Global Change and Natural Systems, Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research (PIK), P.O. Box 60 12 0, D-14412 Potsdam, Germany, Joint Centre for Hydro-Meteorological Research (JCHMR), Met Office, Wallingford OX10 8BB, United Kingdom; Smith, B., Physical Geography and Ecosystems Analysis, Geobiosphere Science Centre, Lund University, Sölvegatan 12, S-22362 Lund, Sweden; Hatterman, F., Department of Global Change and Natural Systems, Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research (PIK), P.O. Box 60 12 0, D-14412 Potsdam, Germany","Dynamic global vegetation models (DGVMs) have been shown to broadly reproduce seasonal and interannual patterns of carbon exchange, as well as realistic vegetation dynamics. To assess the uncertainties in these results associated with model parameterization, the Lund-Potsdam-Jena-DGVM (LPJ-DGVM) is analyzed in terms of model robustness and key sensitive parameters. Present-day global land-atmosphere carbon fluxes are relatively well constrained, despite considerable uncertainty in global net primary production mainly propagating from uncertainty in parameters controlling assimilation rate, plant respiration and plant water balance. In response to climate change, water-use efficiency driven increases in net carbon assimilation by plants, transient changes in vegetation composition and global warming effects on soil organic matter dynamics are robust model results. As a consequence, long-term trends in land-atmosphere fluxes are consistently modeled despite an uncertainty range of -3.35 ± 1.45 PgC yr-1 at the end of the twenty-first century for the specific scenario used. Copyright 2005 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"biosphere; carbon; vegetation",,,,,,"Andreae, M.O., Merlet, P., Emission of trace gases and aerosols from biomass burning (2001) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 15 (4), pp. 955-966; Beringer, J., McIlwaine, S., Lynch, A.H., Chapin, F.S., Bonan, G.B., The use of a reduced form model to assess the sensitivity of a land surface model to biotic surface parameters (2002) Clim. Dyn., 19, pp. 455-466; Campolongo, F., Kleijnen, J., Andres, T., Screening Methods (2000) Sensitivity Analysis, pp. 65-80. , edited by A. Saltelli, K. Chan, and E. M. Scott, John Wiley, Hoboken, N. J; Ciais, P., A three-dimensional synthesis study of delta O-18 in atmospheric CO2: 1. Surface fluxes (1997) J. Geophys. Res., 102 (D5), pp. 5857-5872; Clark, D.A., Brown, S., Kicklighter, D.W., Chambers, J.Q., Thomlinson, J.R., Ni, J., Measuring net primary production in forests: Concepts and field methods (2001) Ecol. Appl., 11 (2), pp. 356-370; Cox, P.M., Betts, R.A., Jones, C.D., Spall, S.A., Totterdell, L.J., Acceleration of global warming due to carbon-cycle feedbacks in a coupled climate model (2000) Nature, 408 (6813), p. 750; Cramer, W., Kicklighter, D.W., Bondeau, A., Moore, B., Churkina, C., Nemry, B., Ruimy, A., Schloss, A.L., Comparing global models of terrestrial net primary productivity (NPP): Overview and key results (1999) Global Change Biol., 5, pp. 1-15; Cramer, W., Global response of terrestrial ecosystem structure and functi